            <font color="white"><b><i>About Hydrothermal Vents</i> </b></font>
          </p>

      <!--text block in right div for sunlight zone information-->
        <p style="font-family:verdana">
          <font color="white">
          
          Hydrothermal vents are like an underwater hot spring. They emerge by seawater bubbling through fissures in ocean
    crust near subduction zones (tectonic plates that move towards or away from one another).  Hot magma and hot mineral-rich water 
    rise and mix with the cold sea water above it, The vent structures are formed from the cooling and solidifying of the mineral 
    deposits.  The water from hydrothermal vents can reach over 700Â° F, but can't boil because of the intense pressure at the depths
    of the abyssal zone.<BR><BR>

    The openings from the sea floor releases hot mineral-rich water, necessary for the unique organisms and ecosystems that they support.
    The bacteria on the vents are able to change the toxic vent minerals to more applicable energy, which then supplies food for the 
    other vent organisms.  This process is called chemosynthesis.<BR><BR>
    
    Vents can differ in chemical and physical aspects, mainly the temperatures, minerals, and flow levels of their plumes.  
    These differences have created black smokers and white smokers.  Black smokers can form chimneys of up to 180 feet.  
    They release the darkest and hottest plumes with high amounts of sulfur.  White smokers form much smaller chimneys and release 
    cooler, weaker flows (called seeps).  They are lighter in color compared to their dark counterparts and have a lot of calcium, 
    silicon, and barium.<BR><BR>
          
          </font>
        </p>
      </div>

